t me re-read the EventBus. The handlers are module-level. Each test's `beforeEach` creates a new EventBus and registers handlers. But old handlers from previous tests still exist. That would cause double-firing.\n\nBut the passing tests (\"reserves stock on order.created\") work fine. Let me think about test order... The first inventory test passes because no prior handlers. Then for \"releases stock on order.cancelled\" test, there are now 2 sets of handlers for CREATED. So when it emits CREATED, the old handler (from test 1) also runs but its `this.repo` refers to the OLD repository. The old repo doesn't have SKU-1 stock, so it fails with \"Insufficient stock\".\n\nThe fix: EventBus should clear global handlers in the constructor, OR each instance should have its own handlers (not global). But we can't change tests. Let me check if any test depends on global handlers...\n\nLooking at the test setup, each test creates a `new EventBus()` — so making handlers instance-level would work. But the globalHandlers design is intentional for cross-service communication (all services sharing the same bus instance). In the tests, they all share the same `bus` instance within a test. The problem is leaking between tests.\n\nThe simplest fix: make EventBus clear global handlers in the constructor. OR better yet: make handlers instance-level instead of module-level.\n\nLet me re-examine: within a single test, OrderService, InventoryService, and BillingService all use the same `bus` instance. So instance-level handlers would work fine.\n\n3. **BillingService.handleRefund** (line 25): `this.eventBus.on(ORDER_EVENTS.REFUNDED, this.handleRefund)` — missing `.bind(this)`, so `this` is undefined when handler runs.\n\n4. **calculateOrderTotal** (line 23): `total = afterDiscount + taxAmount` — both `afterDiscount` and `taxAmount` are individually rounded, but `total` isn't rounded. Need `Math.round(total * 100) / 100`.\n\n5. **OrderService.cancelOrder** — the test expects cancellation to